<h1>Iris Dataset Classification</h1>

<p>This project involves the classification of the Iris dataset using various machine learning algorithms. The goal is to accurately predict the species of iris flowers based on their features.</p>

<h2>Overview</h2>

<p>The Iris dataset is a classic dataset used for classification tasks in machine learning. It contains 150 samples of iris flowers, with four features: sepal length, sepal width, petal length, and petal width. The dataset is divided into three classes, each representing a different species of iris.</p>

<h2>Project Details</h2>

<h3>Libraries Used</h3>
<ul>
    <li><code>sklearn</code>: For machine learning algorithms and dataset handling</li>
    <li><code>pandas</code>: For data manipulation and analysis</li>
    <li><code>numpy</code>: For numerical operations</li>
    <li><code>seaborn</code>: For data visualization</li>
    <li><code>matplotlib</code>: For plotting graphs</li>
</ul>

<h3>Steps Followed</h3>
<ol>
    <li><strong>Loading the Dataset:</strong> The Iris dataset is loaded from the <code>sklearn.datasets</code> module.</li>
    <li><strong>Data Preparation:</strong> A DataFrame is created with feature names and target labels.</li>
    <li><strong>Exploratory Data Analysis:</strong>
        <ul>
            <li>Displaying the DataFrame</li>
            <li>Statistical summary of the data</li>
            <li>Checking for missing values</li>
            <li>Computing the correlation matrix</li>
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li><strong>Data Splitting:</strong> The dataset is split into training and testing sets.</li>
    <li><strong>Model Training:</strong> A Logistic Regression model is trained on the training set.</li>
    <li><strong>Model Evaluation:</strong>
        <ul>
            <li>Accuracy calculation</li>
            <li>Confusion matrix and classification report</li>
            <li>Visualization of the confusion matrix using a heatmap</li>
        </ul>
    </li>
</ol>

<h3>Loading the Dataset</h3>
<p>The Iris dataset can be loaded directly from the <code>sklearn.datasets</code> module as shown below:</p>

<pre><code>from sklearn.datasets import load_iris

# Load the iris dataset
iris = load_iris()

# Create a DataFrame with feature names and target
iris_df = pd.DataFrame(data=iris.data, columns=iris.feature_names)
iris_df['Species'] = iris.target
</code></pre>

<h2>Results</h2>

<p>The Logistic Regression model achieved an accuracy score on the test set. The confusion matrix and classification report provide detailed insights into the model's performance.</p>

<h2>How to Run</h2>

<ol>
    <li>Clone the repository.</li>
    <li>Install the required libraries: <code>sklearn</code>, <code>pandas</code>, <code>numpy</code>, <code>seaborn</code>, <code>matplotlib</code>.</li>
    <li>Run the code in a Python environment (e.g., Jupyter Notebook, VSCode).</li>
</ol>

<p>Feel free to explore the project and reach out if you have any questions or feedback!</p>

